, what do I leave for the next generations? "The land belongs to God, I will never, ever, try to seize it everywhere, but I would like my kids to have the right to live abundantly on the land they will receive." "In the 80’s, we used to pay only 20 Cedis (30 cent) per year like the farmers. But lately the cost of land has increased, a lot". "Many people have come to buy land. Mostly business people".

These are the words of AdjereGilbert Adokpo a man of 38 years, conscientious of his fatherland and committed to extending the fight for transparency in his country

According to him in this interview fait à la

journalmastufa.com

Ajere Gilbert Adokpo

, an activist for some 5 years in Land and Agricultural fights of Togo, and the author of 'FAIRNESS'-articles in sunfmonline and campustv .

1- Bonjour, Gilbert, je suis content de te connaitre, as-tu une vidéo à nous offrir pour te présenter ?

R-Calme toi, c’est ma première interview et je ne sais pas si je suis calé!

J’aimerais que vous puissiez faire connaître la société Togolaise dans son ensemble (Economie, Sport, Culture). SVP, décrivez-moi en quelques lignes votre activité !

S- Depuis
